description:
Family Name: Nyctaginaceae/Four o'Clock
Grows in sandy areas...hence the name Sand Verbena. Grows between February and September-or May, depending on the website.  Needs rain to grow, but when it does it carpets the area! Fragrant flowers. The round purple clusters make it easy to identify. 
According to southwestdesertflora.com the Desert Sand Verbena is used as a diuretic (Paiute) and as a dressing for burns (Shoshoni).

description:
Family Name: Lamiaceae
This bunch of flowers was when we had rain in the desert. This plant was once a very important food for Native Americans. Too many uses to list here! Most often grown from seed. Tall stalks, and easy to identify as it is one of a kind! 
Flowers from March-June.
The first picture is a close up, the second is the hillside with lots of flower varieties.

Cap: starting as marshmellow shape, to the extreme.  Maturing to freakishly umbonate. 
Gills: free, beginning pink, aging to chocolate-brown.
Partial veil: skirtlike. Immediately staining saturated yellow.
Stipe: pheonolic aroma, staining yellow. 
Habitat: in duff under a roadside cypress.

My experience with A. xantho.. found here in California and in Colorado found caps with much less exaggerated (yet still apparent) block-like umbo.
place_guess: Hearst San Simeon State Park, San Luis Obispo County, US-CA, US
